\begin_layout Standard
The Marist educational community has a social commitment to respond to today's
 society, where the educational proposal must be updated.
 The orientation towards methodological innovation and the culture of continuous
 improvement have become strategic axes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Educational innovation is commitment, effort, collaboration and reflection;
 and to contribute with this, an innovation framework has been developed
 that will allow defining, in a unified way, what is intended to be done
 in the area of innovation for all the education centers that are part of
 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

Maristas Ibérica
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

, in order to establish common criteria that they must be taken into account
 from the model of person to educate, so that each school starts from the
 same base when it comes to addressing in its strategy, the processes related
 to innovation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the Provincial Innovation Framework Document 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maristas2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, among the features of the innovative center are four categories in which
 the options for change in a center can be grouped: structure, technology,
 physical environment and people.
 The lines of strategic development that can be useful in the innovative
 approach of the schools are cooperative learning and collaborative learning.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Cooperative360"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The key resources for innovation are: training, technology, budget and time.
 The purpose of the innovation has to produce some kind of improvement,
 generally solving a need, obtaining better results or maintaining the results,
 reducing the effort necessary to obtain them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all the educational stages there is a similarity regarding the order
 of the elements chosen as the most necessary for the development of innovation:
 the time to prepare activities or programs or improve existing ones, training
 on educational, technological and organizational novelties , and a center
 strategy that sets innovation objectives.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One of the criteria for implementing innovation in a Marist school is that
 of Information and Communication Technologies, where the aim is to promote
 in students the ability to search, analyze, use, produce and share their
 own information, using ICT as transversal knowledge to adequately function
 in digital culture and society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Currently, education faces the challenge of preparing professionals to be
 able to integrate into a world mediated by rapid technological advance.
 Students must be prepared to adapt to the current changing society and
 be able to apply for emerging jobs in the best possible conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Today's students consider themselves digital natives and use technology
 on a daily basis, but in very different ways, depending on their age and
 economic status.
 Educators' job is to make sure they receive the same tools and knowledge
 to help reduce the digital divide.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methodological proposal raises a new technological paradigm, where the
 focus of Information Technology turns to Learning Technology, so that technolog
y serves as a vehicle to achieve meaningful learning by students.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As objectives, the aim is to improve the digital competence of students,
 measuring the evolution in the acquisition of this competence.
 And on the other hand, establish technological tools as elements of methodologi
cal support for teachers, to improve and in some cases enable, the teaching-lear
ning process.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any technological initiative, be it an individual or collective methodological
 proposal, or a technological project of the center, should present common
 characteristics such as, objectives, impact, evaluation of the proposal,
 prior training, necessary resources, dissemination, improvements, safety
 and sustainability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The degree of acquisition of digital competence can be measured, determining
 the level reached by students according to the classification at different
 levels.
 Each of the specific competencies determines the level of acquisition of
 levels based on different skills that the student is able to demonstrate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Department of Education of the Basque Government, through the 
\begin_inset Quotes bld
\end_inset

DECREE 174/2012, of September 11, which approves the Technological Maturity
 Model of the Educational Center (ICT Maturity) and establishes the certificatio
ns and certifying stamps of the different maturity levels of educational
 centers
\begin_inset Quotes brd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EducationDepartment2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proposes a new Technological Modernization plan for educational centers
 in order to adapt them to the society of the current century, as well as
 with the aim of promoting a methodological change in teaching processes
 - learning.
 The plan is focused on the technological updating of the teaching staff,
 the incorporation of digital content in the different subjects, the implementat
ion of telematic platforms that support pedagogical, administrative and
 communication work and relations with the school community.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Educational Maturity Model of the Educational Center will serve as a
 frame of reference with which to compare and to have as a shared objective;
 and to be a guide for the effective and efficient digitization of the pedagogic
al and administrative processes of each educational center.
 This model allows obtaining an exact diagnosis of the technological situation
 of a school, and the improvement path to follow to reach the agreed level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This model allows assessing the degree of digitization of the processes
 of a school and marking the line to follow in terms of technologies, practices
 and capacities of all agents of the educational community, to achieve the
 following levels of technological maturity, taking into account the peculiariti
es and specific needs of each center.
 The model is structured in three levels (basic, medium and advanced) that
 gradually increase the degree of digitization of the processes of an educationa
l center and the involvement of teachers in the use of ICT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Maristak Durango school, belonging to the network of centers of the
 Iberian Marist Province and dependent on the Department of Education of
 the Basque Government, passed the evaluation carried out by the Directorate
 of Educational Innovation of the Basque Government, achieving the Advanced
 Level of ICT maturity in 2018.
\end_layout

